1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 e6 {The most traditional and common response to Nf3 d5 c4. This can lead to a variety of positions.} 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {b3 is played since Qa4+ is no longer a possibility, and thus the pawn must be defended properly.} c5 7. e3 (7. Bb2 Nc6 8. e3) 7... Nc6 8. Bb2 b6 (8... d4 {Aiming to shut down the dark-squared bishop, resulting in a benoni structure.} 9. exd4 cxd4 10. Re1 {Preventing e5, a critical pawn move in the benoni. It is very difficult to actually play e5 due to the weakness of the d4 pawn, and Ne5 in some cases.  Black will aim to play e5-e4, with either Ne8 to play f6-e5-f5-e4, or Re8 to play for e5 after Bf8 or Bc5 (after which white will play Ne5 and get a complicated position)  ** NEEDS MORE ANALYSIS **} Re8 (10... Ne8 11. d3 f6 12. Na3 e5 13. Nc2 Nc7 14. a3 a5) 11. d3 Bc5 (11... Bf8 12. a3 a5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Rxe5 Nd7 15. Rb5) 12. a3 a5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Rxe5 Bd6 15. Rb5) (8... dxc4 9. bxc4 Qd3 10. Qb3 Rd8 11. Rd1) 9. Nc3 Bb7 (9... dxc4 10. bxc4 Bb7 11. Qe2 {[%csl Yf4,Yg4][%cal Gf3e1,Gf2f4,Gg3g4,Ga1d1,Gd2d3] A very common position that gives white a simple plan to pursue with Ne1 f4 g4, and attacking the king.   ** NEEDS MORE ANALYSIS **}) 10. cxd5 exd5 11. d4 {A critical move that will always result in black having a weakness (either hanging pawns or an isolated pawn)  ** NEEDS MORE ANALYSIS **} c4 (11... Ba6 12. Re1 c4 13. Ne5 Na5 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4) (11... Rc8 12. Rc1 Ba6 (12... Re8 13. Ne5 Bf8 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Ne2 Bb7 16. dxc5 bxc5 17. Nf4 Ne4) 13. Re1 c4 14. Ne5 Na5 (14... cxb3 15. Nxd5 Nxe5 16. Rxc8 Bxc8 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. dxe5 Nd7 19. Qxb3) 15. bxc4 Bxc4 16. Rc2 Bb4 17. Qb1 Ba6 18. Rec1) 12. bxc4 dxc4 13. e4 *

