1. Nf3 f5 {Unorthodox variation that leads to a very aggressive game for both sides.} 2. d3 {An uncommon response that leads to a variety of positions.} Nf6 {The most common response.} (2... d5 {Does not play into the gambit structure, opting for a stonewall setup.} 3. c4 {Attempting to undermine a possible stonewall setup} dxc4 4. d4 {The pawn will eventually be won back and white has a comfortable position with strong pawns.} Be6 5. e3 Bd5 (5... Nf6 6. Qc2 b5 7. a4 c6 8. axb5 cxb5 9. b3 cxb3 10. Bxb5+ Nbd7 11. Qd3) 6. b3 cxb3 7. Nc3 e6 (7... bxa2 8. Qa4+ c6 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Bc4 Qd6 11. Qxa2 Nh6 12. O-O Nd7 13. Rb1 b6 14. Be6 g6 15. Ng5 Ng4 16. f4) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. axb3 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Qxb3 12. Rc1) 3. e4 {Gambiting a pawn in hopes of gaining tempo and a strong attack.} fxe4 (3... d6 {Not accepting the pawn, and transforming the position} 4. exf5 Bxf5 5. d4 {Imbalances in this position: 1. Weak e6 square since both d and f pawn have advanced 2. Slightly weak e4 square 3. Black has a weaker king  These imbalances suggest that White should attempt to take control of the e6 square and plant a piece on that square.  Moves: Bd3 and Bxf5, c4 d5 followed by Nd4 Ne6 or Ng5 Ne6, Re1} g6 6. Bd3 Bg7 7. O-O Qd7 8. c4 e6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bxf5 exf5 11. Re1 Nc6 12. d5 Nb8 13. Nd4 Na6 14. Ne6) 4. dxe4 Nxe4 {Accepting the gambit} (4... e5 5. Nxe5 Nxe4 6. Qh5+ g6 7. Nxg6 Nf6 8. Qe5+ Be7 9. Nxh8) 5. Bd3 Nf6 {The most natural but incorrect response that leads to a forced line.} (5... d5 6. Bxe4 dxe4 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Ng5 Ke8 9. Nc3) 6. Ng5 g6 7. h4 {Undermining the kingside on the next move.} d5 (7... c6 8. h5 Qa5+) 8. h5 Bg4 (8... Nxh5 9. Rxh5 gxh5 10. Qxh5+) 9. f3 Bxh5 10. g4 Qd6 11. gxh5 {Black must sacrifice the bishop for two pawns to keep some possible play.} Nxh5 12. Nc3 *

